{"source_key":"sha256-e1239717249ea2ac10e16a58312c29fe","record_index":240,"record_hash":"sha256:867c6af92e79ebac898ab6dbaad321ffc2eb6070434bea44eafa14daee698e0f","timestamp":"2026-05-29T17:55:01.980Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_kind":"file_edit","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: codex-findings-agentlog.md\n+# Findings: PR 13995 / 13996 agent-session association\n+\n+## Summary\n+\n+The issue is upstream in `but-agentlog`, not a display-time bug in\n+`agent-trail`.\n+\n+Agent Trail calls `but_agentlog::projection::project_pr(...)` and renders the\n+projected sessions it receives. The incorrect association is already present in\n+GitMeta indexes and then survives `but-agentlog`'s verification for PR 13996.\n+Agent Trail is faithfully displaying the projection output.\n+\n+The root problem is that `but-agentlog` treats global GitButler workspace state\n+as if it were session-local evidence. When two agent sessions operate against\n+the same worktree with multiple applied GitButler branches, capture observes\n+targets and worktree files from both branches. Later, the verifier interprets a\n+worktree-to-commit transition as proof that the session belongs to the target\n+branch, even when those files were produced by the other concurrent session.\n+\n+## Repro Context\n+\n+The two PRs:\n+\n+- PR 13995: `agent-status-after-default`\n+- PR 13996: `unapply-v3-settings-toggle`\n+\n+The relevant local DBs are:\n+\n+- `[REDACTED:path]`\n+- `[REDACTED:path]`\n+\n+`forge_reviews` in `but.sqlite` has the expected PR facts:\n+\n+```text\n+13995  agent-status-after-default  sha [REDACTED:entropy]\n+13996  unapply-v3-settings-toggle  sha [REDACTED:entropy]\n+```\n+\n+The user-observed symptom matches local agentlog output:\n+\n+```sh\n+but --json agentlog skim branch agent-status-after-default\n+```\n+\n+returns one related session, the status-after session:\n+\n+```text\n[REDACTED:entropy]\n+31 turns\n+```\n+\n+But:\n+\n+```sh\n+but --json agentlog skim branch unapply-v3-settings-toggle\n+```\n+\n+returns two related sessions:\n+\n+```text\n[REDACTED:entropy]  31 turns  # status-after session, wrong here\n[REDACTED:entropy]  8 turns   # unapply session, correct here\n+```\n+\n+## Why This Is Not Agent Trail Rendering\n+\n+Agent Trail's projection boundary is here:\n+\n+```rust\n+// [REDACTED:path]\n+let projection =\n+    projection::project_pr(&repo_path, &request).map_err(TrailProjectionError::Projection)?;\n+```\n+\n+That is a single `but-agentlog` projection call. The rest of Agent Trail flattens\n+and presents the returned sessions. It does not independently decide that a\n+session belongs to PR 13996.\n+\n+The relevant `project_pr` code in `but-agentlog` reads review and branch\n+targets:\n+\n+```rust\n+// [REDACTED:path]\n+let review_sessions = find_related_sessions_limited(\n+    repo_path,\n+    RelatedTarget::Review(review_target.as_str()),\n+    None,\n+)?;\n+let branch_sessions = find_related_sessions_limited(\n+    repo_path,\n+    RelatedTarget::Branch(branch_target.as_str()),\n+    None,\n+)?;\n+```\n+\n+Then it only includes turns whose keys survived `find_related_sessions_limited`.\n+So the bad session is already a `but-agentlog` read/projection result before\n+Agent Trail sees it.\n+\n+## GitMeta Evidence\n+\n+The target hashes for the two PRs are:\n+\n+```text\n+13995 branch ref:refs/heads/agent-status-after-default\n+gitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:branch:sha256-b28cef2fc61311a4ff66fd1c997aa72aa053faa0a55a729aa29dcc083c6b66e9\n+\n+13995 review pull-request:ref:refs/heads/agent-status-after-default#13995\n+gitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:review:[REDACTED:entropy]\n+\n+13996 branch ref:[REDACTED:entropy]\n+gitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:branch:sha256-7180b0a56890d604f668dd7c3590a2a665fa65281d0a50a4564cae26232fac82\n+\n+13996 review pull-request:ref:[REDACTED:entropy]#13996\n+gitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:review:sha256-f105da891a40b7595aafc1df00bb03e13f3585fbf82a72a9c1b1a0b577dd5938\n+```\n+\n+The GitMeta index contains both sessions under both PR targets:\n+\n+```text\n+13995 branch:\n+  [REDACTED:entropy]  31 turns\n+  sha256-2aa7526ee83b80afcc1a21d18443cec0   8 turns\n+\n+13995 review:\n+  [REDACTED:entropy]  31 turns\n+  sha256-2aa7526ee83b80afcc1a21d18443cec0   8 turns\n+\n+13996 branch:\n+  [REDACTED:entropy]  31 turns\n+  sha256-2aa7526ee83b80afcc1a21d18443cec0   8 turns\n+\n+13996 review:\n+  [REDACTED:entropy]  31 turns\n+  sha256-2aa7526ee83b80afcc1a21d18443cec0   8 turns\n+```\n+\n+The session-level `associated-targets` values are also over-broad. For example,\n+the status-after session has all of these associated targets:\n+\n+```json\n+{\n+  \"branches\": [\n+    \"ref:refs/heads/agent-status-after-default\",\n+    \"ref:refs/heads/kv-branch-21\",\n+    \"ref:refs/heads/kv-branch-22\",\n+    \"ref:[REDACTED:entropy]\"\n+  ],\n+  \"reviews\": [\n+    \"pull-request:ref:refs/heads/agent-status-after-default#13995\",\n+    \"pull-request:ref:[REDACTED:entropy]#13996\"\n+  ],\n+  \"changes\": [\n+    \"gitbutler-change:ktzpxyytktvtmmvoqvuuysvtuoqtynxw\",\n+    \"gitbutler-change:llqznyvsownzymvsztltvxyrnxqspzou\",\n+    \"gitbutler-change:mookwsqrrxmvmzlozwtnlltuvostwlst\",\n+    \"gitbutler-change:rlptvxxtwvxqzzmrkpukzntzwwtxkqym\",\n+    \"gitbutler-change:uxqmwvozwmnynwsqmynywnvtptxnmluw\",\n+    \"gitbutler-change:wmuyppstxtksplrmpvulzxspmtsluvzw\"\n+  ]\n+}\n+```\n+\n+The unapply session also has both PRs in `associated-targets`.\n+\n+That tells us capture/indexing already made the relation too broad. Display did\n+not invent it.\n+\n+## Why 13996 Shows the Wrong Session But 13995 Does Not\n+\n+There is an important asymmetric verification step.\n+\n+`find_related_sessions_limited` does not blindly trust the index. It calls\n+`turn_detail_observes_target(...)`, which checks:\n+\n+1. Does this turn directly observe the target?\n+2. Or does the session's accumulated `associated-targets` observe it?\n+3. And does the session have target activity according to\n+   `session_has_target_activity(...)`?\n+\n+Relevant code:\n+\n+```rust\n+// [REDACTED:path]\n+if !observed_targets_observe(&detail.observed_targets, target)\n+    && !session_associations_observe_target(handle, &hit.session_key, target)?\n+{\n+    return Ok(false);\n+}\n+\n+let matches = session_has_target_activity(handle, &hit.session_key, target)?;\n+```\n+\n+`session_has_target_activity(...)` accepts either:\n+\n+- a previous turn did not observe the target, then a later turn observes a\n+  sufficiently specific target; or\n+- a previous worktree file appears in a new commit on the target.\n+\n+The second condition is the one that bites here:\n+\n+```rust\n+// [REDACTED:path]\n+environment_promotes_worktree_to_target(previous, current, target)\n+```\n+\n+That helper is documented as:\n+\n+```rust\n+// Strong association: files dirty in one turn show up in a new commit on the\n+// target in the next turn. Ambient applied branches stay weak.\n+```\n+\n+That assumption is good for a single session in a quiet worktree. It is wrong\n+when two sessions share one worktree.\n+\n+## The Exact False-Positive Path\n+\n+The status-after session is:\n+\n+```text\n[REDACTED:entropy]\n+```\n+\n+Its turn 28, captured at `2026-05-29T16:28:09.376Z`, observed only PR 13995 as a\n+target:\n+\n+```text\n+branches:\n+  ref:refs/heads/agent-status-after-default\n+\n+reviews:\n+  pull-request:ref:refs/heads/agent-status-after-default#13995\n+\n+worktree:\n+  apps/desktop/src/components/settings/ExperimentalSettings.svelte\n+  crates/but-settings/src/api.rs\n+```\n+\n+Those worktree files are unapply-v3 files, not status-after files.\n+\n+Then the same status-after session's turn 29, captured at\n+`2026-05-29T16:35:30.691Z`, observed both branches and both reviews:\n+\n+```text\n+branches:\n+  ref:refs/heads/agent-status-after-default\n+  ref:[REDACTED:entropy]\n+\n+reviews:\n+  pull-request:ref:refs/heads/agent-status-after-default#13995\n+  pull-request:ref:[REDACTED:entropy]#13996\n+\n+worktree:\n+  []\n+```\n+\n+Turn 30 did the same at `2026-05-29T16:37:27.805Z`.\n+\n+At that point, the verifier can say: a previous turn had dirty files, and a later\n+environment has a new commit on `unapply-v3-settings-toggle` that contains those\n+files. Therefore this status-after session has activity for PR 13996.\n+\n+That conclusion is false in this concurrent-session case. The dirty files came\n+from the other session, but the worktree snapshot has no session ownership.\n+\n+## Why The Reverse False Positive Gets Filtered Out\n+\n+The unapply session is:\n+\n+```text\n[REDACTED:entropy]\n+```\n+\n+Its early turns also observed the status-after branch/review:\n+\n+```text\n+turn 0, 2026-05-29T16:21:30.431Z\n+\n+branches:\n+  ref:refs/heads/agent-status-after-default\n+\n+reviews:\n+  pull-request:ref:refs/heads/agent-status-after-default#13995\n+\n+worktree:\n+  apps/desktop/src/components/settings/ExperimentalSettings.svelte\n+  crates/but-settings/src/api.rs\n+```\n+\n+This is why the raw index contains the unapply session under PR 13995.\n+\n+But the verifier rejects that relation when querying\n+`agent-status-after-default`, because the unapply session's dirty files do not\n+promote into a new status-after commit. They promote into the unapply branch.\n+So PR 13995 happens to look correct after verification, even though its raw index\n+also contains the wrong session.\n+\n+That is why the symptom is asymmetric:\n+\n+- 13995 raw index is polluted, but verification filters the unapply session out.\n+- 13996 raw index is polluted, and verification incorrectly accepts the\n+  status-after session because it saw unapply worktree files.\n+\n+## Capture-Time Contributor\n+\n+Capture uses `capture_environment(...)`, which captures both worktree paths and\n+GitButler workspace targets:\n+\n+```rust\n+// [REDACTED:path]\n+environment_from_parts(\n+    worktree_paths(&repo).map_err(|_| SnapshotErrorKind::Diff),\n+    workspace_snapshot(&repo).map_err(|_| SnapshotErrorKind::Workspace),\n+)\n+```\n+\n+`workspace_snapshot_with_meta(...)` walks `but_workspace::head_info(...)` stacks\n+and collects every segment's branch, reviews, and change ids:\n+\n+```rust\n+for stack in info.stacks {\n+    for segment in stack.segments {\n+        let branch = BranchTarget {\n+            key: format!(\"ref:{full_ref_name}\"),\n+            name: ref_info.ref_name.shorten().to_string(),\n+        };\n+        let reviews = review_targets(&branch.key, segment.metadata.as_ref());\n+        observed_targets.branches.push(branch.clone());\n+        observed_targets.reviews.extend(reviews.iter().cloned());\n+    }\n+}\n+```\n+\n+That means target observation is workspace-scoped. In a GitButler workspace with\n+multiple applied branches, a session can observe branches it is not actually\n+working on.\n+\n+Then `write_transcript_batch(...)` accumulates observed targets at the session\n+level and re-indexes all previous turns under all accumulated targets:\n+\n+```rust\n+let original_associations = session_target_associations(&handle, &associated_targets_key)?;\n+let mut target_associations = original_associations.clone();\n+target_associations.add_observed_targets(environment_observation.observed_targets());\n+\n+let mut associated_turn_keys = previous_turn_keys;\n+associated_turn_keys.push(turn_key.clone());\n+let index_hit_members = index_hits_for_turns(session_key, &associated_turn_keys)?;\n+let index_keys = target_associations.index_keys();\n+```\n+\n+This is why one later observation of `unapply-v3-settings-toggle` can cause all\n+31 status-after turns to appear in the 13996 index.\n+\n+## Read/Projection Contributor\n+\n+The read-side verifier was intended to avoid exactly this kind of ambient branch\n+pollution, but its worktree-to-commit heuristic is still based on global\n+worktree state.\n+\n+The problematic rule:\n+\n+```rust\n+fn environment_promotes_worktree_to_target(\n+    previous: &StoredEnvironmentSnapshot,\n+    current: &StoredEnvironmentSnapshot,\n+    target: RelatedTarget<'_>,\n+) -> bool\n+```\n+\n+It checks whether files dirty in one environment appear in a new commit on the\n+target in a later environment. The missing premise is: \"these dirty files were\n+created by this session.\" The stored snapshot cannot prove that.\n+\n+In this fixture, that missing premise is exactly false.\n+\n+## Code/Commit Context\n+\n+Agent Trail currently pins:\n+\n+```toml\n+but-agentlog = { git = \"https://github.com/gitbutlerapp/gitbutler.git\", rev = \"[REDACTED:entropy]\", package = \"but-agentlog\" }\n+```\n+\n+That revision includes `71e021110f Fix sub-agent PR association`, which modified\n+the verifier to preserve spawned sub-agent sessions by accepting sub-agent\n+observations before the strict activity heuristic. That change is not the direct\n+cause here, but it is in the same verifier area.\n+\n+The main false-positive mechanism described above exists in the current local\n+code as well:\n+\n+- capture observes workspace-wide branches/reviews/changes\n+- write accumulates session associations and indexes all turns under them\n+- read verifies via session-level associations plus worktree-to-commit promotion\n+\n+## Practical Conclusion\n+\n+This is a `but-agentlog` association-model bug.\n+\n+The data model currently mixes:\n+\n+- session-local transcript records\n+- workspace-global worktree dirtiness\n+- workspace-global GitButler applied branch state\n+- session-level accumulated targets\n+\n+That combination is too broad for concurrent sessions.\n+\n+Agent Trail should not patch around this by filtering sessions downstream. It\n+does not have enough reliable provenance to know which session owned the dirty\n+worktree files or branch commits. Any downstream heuristic would duplicate\n+storage interpretation and still be brittle.\n+\n+## Recommended Fix Direction\n+\n+The clean fix belongs upstream in `but-agentlog`.\n+\n+Recommended direction:\n+\n+1. Stop treating \"branch appears in workspace observation\" as session ownership.\n+   Branch/review observations from multi-branch workspaces should be weak unless\n+   paired with session-local evidence.\n+\n+2. Do not re-index all previous turns under every accumulated session target\n+   unless the association is specific enough. At minimum, distinguish\n+   \"observed in ambient workspace\" from \"session activity target\".\n+\n+3. Tighten or remove the worktree-to-commit promotion heuristic for concurrent\n+   sessions. It needs a stronger premise than global dirty file path overlap.\n+   Possible stronger signals:\n+   - file edits/tools in the session touched those exact paths\n+   - commits created by commands in that session\n+   - branch was explicitly created/committed/pushed by that session\n+   - target appeared alone/specific at the relevant point\n+\n+4. Keep direct review/branch observations useful, but record evidence strength\n+   explicitly. The projection could then expose \"direct\", \"ambient\", and\n+   \"inferred from worktree promotion\" distinctly, instead of converting all\n+   accepted evidence into related turns.\n+\n+5. Add a regression fixture with two concurrent sessions:\n+   - session A produces branch/PR A\n+   - session B produces branch/PR B\n+   - both branches are applied in the same GitButler workspace\n+   - session A observes files from B while B's work is dirty\n+   - PR B projection must not include session A\n+\n+## Useful Commands Used\n+\n+Inspect PR metadata:\n+\n+```sh\n+sqlite3 -header -column [REDACTED:path] \\\n+  \"SELECT number,title,source_branch,target_branch,sha,created_at,modified_at,html_url\n+   FROM forge_reviews\n+   WHERE number IN (13995,13996);\"\n+```\n+\n+Inspect branch-level agentlog results:\n+\n+```sh\n+but --json agentlog skim branch agent-status-after-default\n+but --json agentlog skim branch unapply-v3-settings-toggle\n+```\n+\n+Inspect sessions:\n+\n+```sh\n+but agentlog show [REDACTED:entropy] --limit 35\n+but agentlog show sha256-2aa7526ee83b80afcc1a21d18443cec0 --limit 12\n+```\n+\n+Compute target index keys:\n+\n+```python\n+import hashlib\n+\n+targets = [\n+    (\"branch\", \"ref:refs/heads/agent-status-after-default\"),\n+    (\"review\", \"pull-request:ref:refs/heads/agent-status-after-default#13995\"),\n+    (\"branch\", \"ref:[REDACTED:entropy]\"),\n+    (\"review\", \"pull-request:ref:[REDACTED:entropy]#13996\"),\n+]\n+\n+for kind, key in targets:\n+    digest = hashlib.sha256(key.encode()).hexdigest()\n+    print(kind, key, f\"gitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:{kind}:sha256-{digest}\")\n+```\n+\n+Inspect raw index members:\n+\n+```sql\n+SELECT sv.value\n+FROM set_values sv\n+JOIN metadata m ON sv.metadata_id = m.rowid\n+WHERE m.key = '<index key>';\n+```\n+\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-29T17:55:01.980Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}